HSH 1 April 2026 Simple Shell User Commands

.SH NAME
shell - simple shell

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B shell [command]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B shell
A simple Unix shell that processes commands entered by the user and executes
them, enabling direct interaction with the OS. Supports both interactive and
non-interactive mode.

.SH BUILTIN COMMANDS

.TP
.B env
Prints the current environment variables.

.TP
.B exit
.I [status]
Exits the shell. If no argument is given, exits with the status of the last
executed command.

.SH EXTERNAL COMMANDS
Any executable program found in the system PATH, or specified by
absolute or relative path.

.SH OPTIONS
None

.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES

.TP
.B PATH
The search path for executable programs. If empty or unset, only absolute
and relative paths will work.

.SH FUNCTIONS

.TP
.B read_line(void)
Reads a line of input from standard input. Displays a prompt in interactive
mode.

.TP
.B tokenize(char *command, char **args, int *argc)
Tokenizes a command string into individual arguments using whitespace
delimiters.

.TP
.B exec_commands(char *command, char *prog_name)
Parses and executes a command. Handles builtins first, then searches PATH.

.TP
.B fork_execute(char **args, char *prog_name)
Forks a new process and executes a command using execve.

.TP
.B command_path(char *command)
Returns the full path of a command, checking absolute/relative paths or
searching PATH.

.TP
.B find_in_path(char *filename)
Searches each directory in PATH for the given executable.

.TP
.B _getenv(const char *name)
Custom implementation of .B getenv. Searches the environment list for
a variable by name.

.TP
.B builtin_commands(char **args, char *command)
Handles built-in commands: exit and env.

.TP
.B print_env(void)
Prints all current environment variables to standard output.

.SH EXIT STATUS

.TP
.B 0
Success.

.TP
.B 127
Command not found.

.TP
.B other
Exit status of the last executed command when using exit with no
argument.

